The NESTROFT test, also known as the osmotic fragility test, is commonly used to screen for hereditary spherocytosis, which is characterized by increased red blood cell (RBC) fragility due to abnormalities in RBC membrane proteins. This test assesses how well RBCs survive in varying concentrations of saline solution, making it a valuable tool for detecting conditions where RBCs are more susceptible to hemolysis. While the test can be relevant to other types of anemia, its primary application is in diagnosing hereditary spherocytosis. Therefore, option B is the most accurate choice among the given options. Options A, C, and D represent different types of anemia for which specific tests exist but do not align with the primary purpose of the NESTROFT test.
Final Answer: \boxed{B}

